[[File:DarkHorse AMPV.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Soldiers from 4th Squadron (Dark Horse), [[9th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|9th Cavalry Regiment]], 2nd Armored Brigade Combat Team, [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]], complete field testing of the Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle at [[Fort Hood]], Texas, 2018]]
[[File:Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle (AMPV).jpg|thumb|Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle (AMPV)]]
The '''Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle''' ('''AMPV''') is an American [[armored fighting vehicle]] that is replacing the [[M113 armored personnel carrier]] and family of vehicles in U.S. Army service.<ref name="rationale">{{cite web |last=Freedberg Jr |first=Sydney J. |date=29 May 2012 |title=Army Mulls $1.7 Billion Effort To Replace 3,000 M113s |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2012/05/army-mulls-1-7-billion-effort-to-replace-3-000-m113s/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231230011918/https://breakingdefense.com/2012/05/army-mulls-1-7-billion-effort-to-replace-3-000-m113s/ |archive-date=30 December 2023 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref> The AMPV was designed and produced by [[BAE Systems]], and is based on the [[Bradley Fighting Vehicle]].<ref name="BAE AMPV">{{Cite web |last=McLeary |first=Paul |date=24 December 2014 |title=Army Awards AMPV to BAE Systems, Future Fights Loom |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2014/12/24/army-awards-ampv-to-bae-systems-future-fights-loom/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20141224182019/http://www.defensenews.com/story/defense/land/army/2014/12/23/army-ampv-armor/20835861/ |archive-date=24 December 2014 |access-date=24 December 2014 |website=Defense News}}</ref>

{{As of|2013}}, five variants of the 2,907 AMPV are planned:

* M1283 general purpose (522 planned)
* M1284 medical evacuation vehicle (790 planned)
* M1285 medical treatment vehicle (216 planned)
* M1286 [[mission command]] (993 planned)
* M1287 mortar carrier vehicle (386 planned)<ref name="RFP">{{cite web |last=Freedberg Jr |first=Sydney J. |date=22 March 2013 |title=Army Issues RFP For $6 Billion M113 Replacement: Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle Program |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2013/03/army-issues-rfp-for-6-billion-m113-replacement-armored-multi-p/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231230011919/https://breakingdefense.com/2013/03/army-issues-rfp-for-6-billion-m113-replacement-armored-multi-p/ |archive-date=30 December 2023 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref>

The first AMPV prototype was rolled out in December 2016<ref>{{cite web |last=Judson |first=Jen |date=15 December 2016 |title=BAE Systems Presents First AMPV Prototype to US Army |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2016/12/15/bae-systems-presents-first-ampv-prototype-to-us-army |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200302155557/https://www.defensenews.com/land/2016/12/15/bae-systems-presents-first-ampv-prototype-to-us-army/ |archive-date=2 March 2020 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |website=Defense News}}</ref> Following a competitive bidding process, the first production vehicles were delivered 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cox |first=Matthew |date=2 September 2020 |title=Army Set to Receive First Armored Vehicles to Replace Vietnam-Era M113 |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2020/09/02/army-set-receive-first-armored-vehicles-replace-vietnam-era-m113.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230316215459/https://www.military.com/daily-news/2020/09/02/army-set-receive-first-armored-vehicles-replace-vietnam-era-m113.html |archive-date=16 March 2023 |website=military.com}}</ref> In 2023 the AMPV entered full-rate initial production.<ref name="Jones" >{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Colton |date=5 August 2023 |title=US Army's new armored vehicle enters full-rate production |url=https://defence-blog.com/us-armys-new-armored-vehicle-enters-full-rate-production/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231029213504/https://defence-blog.com/us-armys-new-armored-vehicle-enters-full-rate-production/ |archive-date=29 October 2023 |website=Defence Blog}}</ref>

==Rationale==
[[File:US Army AMPV compared to the M113.png|thumb|{{legend|#b49c6c|The AMPV has 78% more interior volume compared to}} {{legend|#4e4e4e| the M113 armored personnel carrier}}]]

The M113 has been in service since the early 1960s and while able to take on various roles, has proven too vulnerable for combat. In the 1980s, the [[M2 Bradley]] replaced the M113 in the [[Front line|front-line]] transport role, moving it to [[Rear (military)|rear-area]] roles. In the [[Iraq War]], [[urban warfare]] tactics still defeated the M113, leading it to be almost entirely replaced in active service by [[Mine-Resistant Ambush Protected Vehicle]]s (MRAP). MRAPs were useful on the roads of Iraq, but have less payload capacity and worse off-road performance. The AMPV aims to find a vehicle more versatile and mobile against a wide range of adversaries while having off-road mobility comparable to Bradleys and [[M1 Abrams]] tanks.<ref name="rationale"/>

Some reports suggested that the AMPV program was being favored over the [[Ground Combat Vehicle]] (GCV) program. While procurement of the AMPV fleet would cost over $5 billion, the [[Government Accountability Office]] estimates the GCV fleet would cost $37 billion. In April 2013, the [[Congressional Budget Office]] said the AMPV would be a better buy because analysts have asserted that the vehicles the GCV is slated to replace should not be first. The GCV was to replace 61 [[M2 Bradley]] [[infantry fighting vehicle]]s in each armored combat brigade, making up 18 percent of the 346 armored combat vehicles in each armored brigade.<ref name="favor"/>

A September 2013 [[Congressional Research Service]] report suggested that given budgetary constraints, the GCV program may be unrealistic, and that one potential discussion could focus on a decision by the Army to replace the GCV with the AMPV as their number one ground combat vehicle acquisition priority.<ref name="favor">{{cite web|last=McLeary|first=Paul|url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20131002/DEFREG02/310020011/US-Army-Looks-Delay-Increase-Cost-AMPV-Program|title=US Army Looks To Delay, Increase Cost of AMPV Program|website=Defense News|date=2 October 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131006111913/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20131002/DEFREG02/310020011/US-Army-Looks-Delay-Increase-Cost-AMPV-Program|archive-date=6 October 2013|access-date=6 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Army FY 2015 budget proposal suggests canceling the GCV program and moving funds to the AMPV as the service's priority vehicle program.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cox |first=Matthew |date=4 March 2014 |title=Army 2015 Budget Kills GCV, Cuts Readiness |url=http://www.dodbuzz.com/2014/03/04/army-2015-budget-kills-gcv-cuts-readiness/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306015030/http://www.dodbuzz.com/2014/03/04/army-2015-budget-kills-gcv-cuts-readiness/ |archive-date=6 March 2014 |website=DoD Buzz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Vergun |first=David |date=4 March 2014 |title=FY15 Army budget: request includes small pay raise, 490K end strength |url=https://www.army.mil/article/121217/FY15_Army_budget__request_includes_small_pay_raise__490K_end_strength/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231010134839/https://www.army.mil/article/121217/FY15_Army_budget__request_includes_small_pay_raise__490K_end_strength/ |archive-date=10 October 2023 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |website=U.S. Army}}</ref>

In order to keep development costs down, the Army is requiring the vehicle be a [[commercial off-the-shelf]] design that can be incrementally improved. The vehicle would have new technologies including electronics, networking, and communications gear added onto the platform as they become available later. If the AMPV can incorporate newer [[satellite communications]] as they are developed, they could be linked to other ground vehicles that would normally require a complete subsystems overhaul for new gear after a certain number of years.<ref>{{cite web |last=Osborn |first=Kris |date=31 October 2013 |title=Army Mulls Trading New Vehicles for Upgrades to Old Ones |url=http://www.dodbuzz.com/2013/10/31/army-mulls-trading-new-vehicles-for-upgrades-to-old-ones/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923221536/http://www.dodbuzz.com/2013/10/31/army-mulls-trading-new-vehicles-for-upgrades-to-old-ones/ |archive-date=23 September 2015 |website=DoD Buzz}}</ref> The operational maintenance cost requirement of the AMPV is up to $90 per mile, compared to $58 per mile for the M113.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gourley |first=Scott R. |date=7 November 2013 |title=Abrams Dieselization Project: Doing the Math |url=http://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/abrams-dieselization-project-doing-the-math/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231010134020/https://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/abrams-dieselization-project-doing-the-math/ |archive-date=10 October 2023 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |website=Defense Media Network}}</ref>

==History==
In March 2013, the Army issued a draft [[request for proposal]]s (RFP) for the AMPV. The RFP proposed a $1.46 billion contract for design and development phases. The engineering and manufacturing development (EMD) phase would build 29 prototypes over four years from 2014 through 2017 for $388 million. [[Low rate initial production|Low-rate initial production]] (LRIP) would be from 2018 to 2020 at $1.08 billion for 289 production models. After 2020, the Army planned to buy another 2,618 vehicles over ten years for a total of 2,907 AMPVs. Cost per vehicle is not to exceed $1.8 million, totalling $4.7 billion for the entire fleet.<ref name="RFP"/>

In October 2013, the Army released a new draft RFP, delaying the start of the program by one year and raising the development costs by several hundred million dollars. The new document said the Army planned to award a five-year EMD contract in May 2014 to one contractor, which will manufacture 29 vehicles for government testing, followed by a three-year LRIP contract starting in 2020. The EMD phase was extended from FY 2015 to FY 2019, and raised the cost to build 29 prototypes to $458 million.<ref name="favor"/>

Expenditures for three years of LRIP for 289 vehicles were $244 million the first year, $479 million the second year, and $505 million the third year, totaling an increase to $1.2 billion for low-rate production. The AMPV will cost $1.68 billion before full-rate production begins, an increase from $1.46 billion previously. The new draft did not change the total number of vehicles desired and does not include an average unit manufacturing cost. Congress approved $116 million for the program in the Army's FY 2014 budget.<ref name="favor"/>

The AMPV has a relatively long production schedule for a non-developmental vehicle of 13 years: 3 years for low-rate production and 10 years for full-rate production. The production plan was partly based on budgetary constraints, but also to be able to speed up production in the event of war or another contingency. 33 percent of an Armored [[Brigade combat team|Brigade Combat Team]] (ABCT) is made up of M113s, which are not used in combat operations because they are less mobile and poorly protected than other combat vehicles in an ABCT. Full-rate production should build just under 300 AMPV vehicles per year, but the ability is there to quickly increase production if an ABCT needed to deploy to combat. Letting industry build as fast as possible regularly only to stop it later is seen as irresponsible.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wasserbly |first=Daniel |date=22 October 2013 |title=AUSA 2013: Army envisions AMPV production spike for emergency contingencies |url=http://www.janes.com/article/28836/ausa-2013-army-envisions-ampv-production-spike-for-emergency-contingencies |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029185711/http://www.janes.com/article/28836/ausa-2013-army-envisions-ampv-production-spike-for-emergency-contingencies |archive-date=29 October 2013 |work=[[Jane's International Defence Review]]}}</ref>

In November 2013, the Army released the official AMPV EMD phase RFP. Despite sequestration budget cuts, the program is maintaining its previously stated goal of 2,907 vehicles at $1.8 million each, built over 13 years. A 5-year EMD contract was to be awarded to one manufacturer in May 2014 to produce 29 vehicles for testing. Although the October draft RFP raised the cost of the EMD phase to $458 million, the official November RFP lowered it to $436 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=McLeary |first=Paul |date=26 November 2013 |title=Army releases RFP for new armored vehicle |url=http://www.armytimes.com/article/20131126/NEWS/311260025/Army-releases-RFP-new-armored-vehicle |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20131128163010/http://www.armytimes.com/article/20131126/NEWS/311260025/Army-releases-RFP-new-armored-vehicle |archive-date=28 November 2013 |access-date=28 November 2013 |work=[[Army Times]]}}</ref>

Annual expenditures for the EMD phase are $70 million in FY 2015, $174 million in FY 2016, $114 million in FY 2017, $64 million in FY 2018, and $14 million in FY 2019. The RFP also contains an Optional Exchange Vehicle (OEV) program to exchange up to 78 vehicles during the EMD phase for AMPVs. 39 Bradley vehicles of versions previous to the current M2A3/M3A3 configurations and 39 M113s not including the M113 AMEV can be exchanged by the government to the contractor for credit.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gourley |first=Scott R. |date=10 December 2013 |title=Army Releases Final RFP for Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle (AMPV) |url=http://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/army-releases-final-rfp-for-ampv-part-i/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221228095004/https://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/army-releases-final-rfp-for-ampv-part-i/ |archive-date=28 December 2022 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |website=Defense Media Network}}</ref>

===RFP issues===
In February 2014, [[General Dynamics]] filed a protest with the [[United States Army Materiel Command|Army Materiel Command]] on grounds that the AMPV requirements had been written to favor a chassis based on the [[BAE Systems]] [[Bradley Fighting Vehicle]], making it more difficult for their [[Stryker]] designs or other foreign designs to compete in the program. They cite the option of using excess Bradleys as optional exchange vehicles, which is difficult for a competitor not offering the chassis, the Army not providing performance data on Bradley components outside of BAE, which they could use to develop a tracked offering, and mobility requirements that exclude wheeled vehicles, which call for a vehicle that can go 100 percent of places the M113 is able to, including very soft ground.<ref name="McLeary290314">{{cite web|last=McLeary|first=Paul|url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140329/DEFREG02/303290021/More-Disputes-Likely-US-Army-s-AMPV-Contest?odyssey=mod_sectionstories|title=More Disputes Likely in US Army's AMPV Contest|website=Defense News|date=29 March 2014|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140330185845/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140329/DEFREG02/303290021/More-Disputes-Likely-US-Army-s-AMPV-Contest?odyssey=mod_sectionstories|archive-date=30 March 2014|access-date=30 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="breakingdefense1april14"/>

BAE said the Army's changed mobility requirements from a zero turning radius to a larger turning radius that could accommodate a wheeled design and that requirements do not specify a Bradley-based vehicle because a pure Bradley solution would not meet them; the AMPV's survivability requirements are higher than that of an M2 equipped with the [[Bradley Fighting Vehicle#Bradley Urban Survival Kit|Bradley Urban Survival Kit (BUSK) III]].<ref name="McLeary290314" /><ref name="breakingdefense1april14">{{cite web |last=Freedberg Jr |first=Sydney J. |date=1 April 2014 |title=General Dynamics: We Can't Compete For AMPV Unless Army Changes Course |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2014/04/general-dynamics-we-just-cant-compete-for-ampv-unless-army-changes-course/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221111063703/https://breakingdefense.com/2014/04/general-dynamics-we-just-cant-compete-for-ampv-unless-army-changes-course/ |archive-date=11 November 2022 |accessdate=2 April 2014 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref>

The Army Materiel Command denied General Dynamics' protest in April 2014. Their response was that although BAE had an advantage being the manufacturers of the Bradley and M113, the government was not required to neutralize that and that does not constitute preferential treatment. Regarding OEVs, the Army Materiel Command clarified that they may not specifically be used for conversion but could still be exchanged for foreign sales or be scrapped, which would be less cost-effective. General Dynamics could have gone to the [[Government Accountability Office]] with its protest, or simply withdraw from the competition.<ref name="breakingdefense1april14"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Freedberg Jr |first=Sydney J. |date=4 April 2014 |title=Denied: Army Rejects General Dynamics Protest On AMPV Program; GD, BAE Respond |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2014/04/denied-army-rejects-general-dynamics-protest-on-ampv-program-gd-bae-respond/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220416233932/https://breakingdefense.com/2014/04/denied-army-rejects-general-dynamics-protest-on-ampv-program-gd-bae-respond/ |archive-date=16 April 2022 |accessdate=4 April 2014 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref> In April 2014, General Dynamics released a statement saying they wouldn't file a protest with the GAO, but would still be engaged in talks with Congress and the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]]. AMPV proposals were due by 28 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web |last=Freedberg Jr |first=Sydney J. |date=15 April 2014 |title=Tank Wars: General Dynamics Won't Protest AMPV To GAO, Targets Hill |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2014/04/tank-wars-general-dynamics-wont-take-ampv-protest-to-gao-but-will-to-hill/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220708164647/https://breakingdefense.com/2014/04/tank-wars-general-dynamics-wont-take-ampv-protest-to-gao-but-will-to-hill/ |archive-date=8 July 2022 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref>

===Vehicle submissions===
[[File:Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle.jpg|thumb|The AMPV at the U.S. Army [[Fort Greely, Alaska|Cold Regions Test Center]]]]
[[File:Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle - 230921-O-WJ404-2116.jpg|thumb|A [[3rd Infantry Division (United States)|3rd ID]]'s AMPV drives off of a 497th Multi-Role Bridge Company, 92nd Engineer Battalion barge during a wet-gap crossing exercise on Fort Stewart's Pineview Lake, September 2023.]]

In May 2014, BAE Systems submitted their proposal for the AMPV competition. Their submission was based on the Bradley and [[M109 howitzer#M109A7|Paladin Integrated Management]] designs to meet the force protection and all-terrain mobility requirements with maximum commonality within the family of vehicles. The BAE AMPV team includes: [[DRS Technologies]] for power management, distribution, and integration; [[Northrop Grumman]] for Mission Command Mission Equipment Package design and integration; [[Air Methods Corporation]] for medical evacuation and treatment subsystems; and the [[Red River Army Depot]] for vehicle teardown and component remanufacture.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gray |first=Alicia |date=28 May 2014 |title=BAE Systems Submits Bid for Highly Survivable, Affordable Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle |url=http://www.baesystems.com/article/BAES_167495/bae-systems-submits-bid-for-highly-survivable-affordable-armored-multi-purpose-vehicle |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230201024016/https://www.baesystems.com/en/article/bae-systems-submits-bid-for-highly-survivable-affordable-armored-multipurpose-vehicle |archive-date=1 February 2023 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |website=BAE Systems}}</ref>

===Split buy proposal===

The FY2015 [[National Defense Authorization Act]] legislative language called for further examination of the use of wheeled AMPV variants at both echelons above brigade (EAB) as well as for medical evacuation purposes.<ref name="Feickert" >{{cite report |last= Feickert |first=Andrew |date=14 September 2016 |title=The Army's Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle (AMPV): Background and Issues for Congress  |url=https://apps.dtic.mil/sti/tr/pdf/AD1017540.pdf |work=Congressional Research Service |access-date=14 September 2025}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>

General Dynamics had lobbied for a split buy, arguing that a split buy of its Strykers would save the Army $2 billion in life cycle costs and that it is smoother and quicker than a tracked vehicle in the role.<ref>{{cite web|last=McLeary|first=Paul|url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140629/DEFREG02/306290016/US-Armored-Vehicle-Battle-Intensifies|title=US Armored Vehicle Battle Intensifies|website=Defense News|date=29 June 2014|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140707085459/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140629/DEFREG02/306290016/US-Armored-Vehicle-Battle-Intensifies|archive-date=7 July 2014|access-date=5 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="breakingdefense1may14">{{cite web |last=Freedberg Jr |first=Sydney J. |date=1 May 2014 |title=HASC Throws General Dynamics Little Bone On AMPV |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2014/05/hasc-throws-general-dynamics-little-bone-on-ampv/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231023100946/https://breakingdefense.com/2014/05/hasc-throws-general-dynamics-little-bone-on-ampv/ |archive-date=23 October 2023 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Cox |first=Matthew |date=20 May 2014 |title=MRAPs Join Competition to Replace Troop Carriers |url=http://www.military.com/daily-news/2014/05/20/mraps-join-competition-to-replace-troop-carriers.html?comp=7000023317843&rank=5 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230719225225/https://www.military.com/daily-news/2014/05/20/mraps-join-competition-to-replace-troop-carriers.html?comp=7000023317843&rank=5 |archive-date=19 July 2023 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |website=Military.com}}</ref> [[Navistar Defense]] also advocated this approach, offering its [[MaxxPro]] MRAP to fulfill part of the AMPV role..<ref name="McLeary290314" /><ref name="breakingdefense1april14">{{cite web |last=Freedberg Jr |first=Sydney J. |date=1 April 2014 |title=General Dynamics: We Can't Compete For AMPV Unless Army Changes Course |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2014/04/general-dynamics-we-just-cant-compete-for-ampv-unless-army-changes-course/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221111063703/https://breakingdefense.com/2014/04/general-dynamics-we-just-cant-compete-for-ampv-unless-army-changes-course/ |archive-date=11 November 2022 |accessdate=2 April 2014 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref>

In a March 2015 report the Army told Congress that wheeled medical vehicles are unsuitable for ABCTs due to the inability to maneuver with highly mobile combat vehicles. For medical evacuations, tracked vehicle's superior mobility better enables it to retrieve wounded soldiers. The requirements were for a vehicle that could go wherever the tracked vehicles of an armored brigade went, which would include rough terrain and soft ground that a wheeled vehicle could get bogged down in, preventing an armored ambulance from reaching wounded soldiers in time. Using BAE's Bradley-based chassis allows for commonality between 75 percent of an armored brigade's combat vehicles, easing maintenance and logistics and ensuring the vehicles have comparable mobility.<ref>{{cite web |last=Freedberg Jr |first=Sydney J. |date=31 March 2015 |title=70-Year-Old M113s: The Army's Long March To AMPV |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2015/03/the-armys-long-march-to-ampv-expect-70-year-old-m113s/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230621030244/https://breakingdefense.com/2015/03/the-armys-long-march-to-ampv-expect-70-year-old-m113s/ |archive-date=21 June 2023 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gould|first=Joe|url=http://www.armytimes.com/story/defense/show-daily/ausa/2015/03/31/us-army-leaders-make-case-for-baes-ampv/70728052/|title=US Army Leaders Make Case for AMPV Decision|work=Army Times|date=31 March 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150406035852/http://www.armytimes.com/story/defense/show-daily/ausa/2015/03/31/us-army-leaders-make-case-for-baes-ampv/70728052/|archive-date=6 April 2015|access-date=5 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>

===EMD===
In December 2014, [[BAE Systems]] was awarded a $383 million contract to begin the Engineering, Manufacturing, and Development (EMD) phase of the AMPV program. The initial award is for a 52-month base term, to produce 29 vehicles across each of the variants. It contains the option to begin Low-Rate Initial Production (LRIP) immediately following the EMD's conclusion to produce an additional 289 vehicles for the total contract value of $1.2 billion.<ref name="BAE AMPV" /><ref name="armyrec241214">{{cite web |date=24 December 2014 |title=BAE Systems wins $1.2 bn contract to launch Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle program |url=http://www.armyrecognition.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=10011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230080633/http://www.armyrecognition.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=10011 |archive-date=30 December 2014 |website=ArmyRecognition.com}}</ref><ref name="BBC241214">{{cite news |date=24 December 2014 |title=BAE wins $1.2bn US combat vehicles contract |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-30597521 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220421132233/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-30597521 |archive-date=21 April 2022 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>

The vehicles are to move as rapidly as the primary combat vehicles in an ABCT during unified land operations over multiple terrain sets with superior force protection, survivability, and mobility than the M113. They will support the M1 Abrams and M2/M3 Bradley to resupply the formation, conduct battle command functions, deliver organic indirect fires, provide logistics support and medical treatment, and perform medical and casualty evacuation to function as an integral part of the ABCT formation.<ref name="BAE AMPV" /><ref name="armyrec241214" /><ref name="BBC241214" />

===Production===
{{expand section|date=September 2025}}
The first production vehicles were delivered August 2020.<ref name="First deliveries">{{cite news |last1=Judson |first1=Jen |title=First Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle for US Army rolls off BAE production line |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2020/09/02/first-armored-multi-purpose-vehicle-for-us-army-rolls-of-bae-production-line/ |access-date=28 September 2025 |work=Defense News |date=2 September 2020 |language=en}}</ref>
In March 2023, the U.S. Army delivered the first AMPVs to the 1st Armored Brigade Combat Team, 3rd Infantry Division at [[Fort Stewart]], Georgia.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Judson |first=Jen |date=14 March 2023 |title=First unit gets new Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicles replacing old M113s |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2023/03/14/first-unit-gets-new-armored-multi-purpose-vehicles-replacing-old-m113s/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230315092013/https://www.defensenews.com/land/2023/03/14/first-unit-gets-new-armored-multi-purpose-vehicles-replacing-old-m113s/ |archive-date=15 March 2023 |access-date=17 March 2023 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref> In August 2023, the AMPV entered full-rate initial production.<ref name="Jones" />

==Variants==
[[File:US Army Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle.jpg|right|thumb|The general purpose and medical evacuation vehicle variants of the AMPV]]
[[File:M1285 Medical Treatment Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle.jpg|thumb|M1285 Medical Treatment Vehicle.]]
There are to be five versions of the AMPV:<ref name="Variants">{{cite web |date=24 April 2012 |title=Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle (AMPV) Industry Day |url=http://www.defenseinnovationmarketplace.mil/resources/ArmoredMulti-PurposeVehicleProgramIndustryDayCharts.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121224053652/http://www.defenseinnovationmarketplace.mil/resources/ArmoredMulti-PurposeVehicleProgramIndustryDayCharts.pdf |archive-date=24 December 2012 |type=Flyer}}</ref>

=== US Army variants ===

==== M1283 general purpose (GP) ====
This variant replaces the M113A3 APC. Requirements are for 2 crew and 4 troops, be configured to carry one litter, and mount a crew served weapon.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news |date=2023-03-14 |title=Army delivers newest combat vehicle |url=https://www.army.mil/article/264804/army_delivers_newest_combat_vehicle |access-date=2025-03-19 |work=US Army}}</ref> Tasks include conducting logistics package escort, emergency resupply, [[casualty evacuation]], and security for [[medical evacuation]]<ref name="Variants" /> and 522 vehicles are planned.<ref name="RFP" />

==== M1284 medical evacuation vehicle (MEV) ====
This variant replaces the [[M113A4 armored medical evacuation vehicle|M113 AMEV]]. Requirements are for 3 crew and able to have either 6 ambulatory patients, 4 litter patients, or 3 ambulatory patients and 2 litter patients.<ref name=":1" /> It must also have medical equipment sets and environmental cooling. Tasks include conducting [[medical evacuation]] from the point of injury to an [[aid station]] and medical resupply replenishment<ref name="Variants" /> and 790 vehicles are planned.<ref name="RFP" />

==== M1285 medical treatment vehicle (MTV) ====
This variant replaces the [[M577A4 armored treatment vehicle|M577A4 medical vehicle]]. Requirements are for 4 crew and one litter patient, as well as medical equipment sets and environmental cooling. Tasks include serving as the forward aid station, main aid station, and [[Battalion Aid Station|battalion aid station]]<ref name="Variants" /> and 216 vehicles are planned.<ref name="RFP" />

==== M1286 Mission Command (MCmd) ====
This variant replaces the [[M577 command post carrier|M1068A3 command post carrier]]. Requirements are for 2 crew, 2 operators, and a mount for a crew served weapon. The task is to serve as a command post<ref name="Variants" /> and 993 vehicles are planned.<ref name="RFP" />

This variant intends to become the cornerstone of the Army's ABCT Network Modernization Strategy.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=15 March 2024 |title=The Army's Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle (AMPV) |url=https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/IF/IF11741/13}}</ref>

==== XM1287 mortar carrier vehicle (MCV) ====
This variant replaces the [[M1064 mortar carrier|M1064A3 mortar carrier]]. Requirements are for 2 crew and 2 mortar crew, with a 120&nbsp;mm mortar and 69 mortar rounds. The task is to provide indirect mortar fire<ref name="Variants" /> and 386 vehicles are planned.<ref name="RFP" /> In 2024, trials of the AMPV equipped with a [[Patria NEMO]] mortar turret took place in Fort Moore, Georgia.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-09-12 |title=U.S. Army demonstrated the capabilities of Patria NEMO 120 mm Turreted Mortar System |url=https://defence-industry.eu/u-s-army-demonstrated-the-capabilities-of-patria-nemo-120-mm-turreted-mortar-system/ |access-date=2024-09-12 |language=en}}</ref>

==== AMPV 30mm ====
[[File:The 1st Cavalry Division fields the new AMPV 30mm 06.jpg|thumb|AMPV 30mm]]

In April 2026, the [[1st Cavalry Division (United States)|1st Cavalry Division]] fielded the new AMPV 30mm at Fort Hood, Texas. The AMPV 30mm is equipped with the [[Kongsberg Defence & Aerospace|Kongsberg]] MCT-30, a remotely operated, unmanned turret. It allows the crew to control the weapon from within the vehicle’s protected hull, reducing their exposure to enemy fire. The unmanned design also removes the need for a turret basket, freeing up internal space.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The 1st Cavalry Division fields the new AMPV 30mm |url=https://www.dvidshub.net/image/9651156/1st-cavalry-division-fields-new-ampv-30mm |access-date=2026-04-30 |website=DVIDS |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-04-30 |title=U.S. Army equips AMPV with 30mm cannon for armored units |url=https://defence-blog.com/u-s-army-equips-ampv-with-30mm-cannon-for-armored-units/ |access-date=2026-04-30 |website=The Defence Blog – Military and Defense News |language=en-US}}</ref>

The 30mm autocannon enables the AMPV to engage lightly armored vehicles and fortified positions and can use programmable airburst ammunition to target small drones and unarmored ground threats. This capability allows the vehicle to provide more direct support to maneuver units, rather than operating solely in support or rear-echelon roles.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The 1st Cavalry Division fields the new AMPV 30mm |url=https://www.dvidshub.net/image/9651156/1st-cavalry-division-fields-new-ampv-30mm |access-date=2026-04-30 |website=DVIDS |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-04-30 |title=U.S. Army equips AMPV with 30mm cannon for armored units |url=https://defence-blog.com/u-s-army-equips-ampv-with-30mm-cannon-for-armored-units/ |access-date=2026-04-30 |website=The Defence Blog – Military and Defense News |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Variants proposed by BAE Systems ===

==== C-UAS ====
In 2024, BAE Systems revealed a variant of the AMPV with a C-UAS turret, the [[Stryker#SHORAD|Leonardo M-SHORAD]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Judson |first=Jen |date=2024-01-23 |title=BAE tests counter-drone capability on Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2024/01/23/bae-tests-counter-drone-capability-on-armored-multi-purpose-vehicle/ |access-date=2024-11-13 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=23 January 2024 |title=BAE Systems Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle prototype successfully fires Counter-Unmanned Aircraft System during live multi-scenario demonstration |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/article/bae-systems-armored-multi-purpose-vehicle-prototype-successfully-fires-counter-unmanned-aircraft-system-during-live-multi-scenario-demonstration |access-date=2024-11-13 |website=www.baesystems.com}}</ref>

==== Engineering vehicle ====
An internal BAE project in collaboration with the US Army to develop an engineer vehicle to replace M113's in that role at Echelons Above Brigade (EAB).<ref>{{cite web |last=Gray |first=Alicia |date=3 April 2018 |title=AMPV: Bringing flexible, multi-mission capabilities to the U.S. Army |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en-us/article/ampv-bringing-flexible-multi-mission-capabilities-to-the-us-army |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221228102407/https://www.baesystems.com/en-us/article/ampv-bringing-flexible-multi-mission-capabilities-to-the-us-army |archive-date=28 December 2022 |accessdate=28 April 2019 |website=BAE Systems}}</ref>

==== Infantry fighting vehicle ====
In October 2024, BAE Systems presented a variant with a remote controlled turret [[Protector RWS#Overview|Kongsberg Protector RT20]] (30&nbsp;mm).<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 October 2024 |title=BAE Systems presents two Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle prototypes equipped with different mission capabilities at AUSA |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/article/bae-systems-presents-two-armored-multi-purpose-vehicle-prototypes-equipped-with-different-mission-capabilities-at-ausa}}</ref>

